TECHNICAL FIELD The present invention relates to a biodegradable laminate obtained by laminating a polyvinyl alcohol-based resin layer on at least one surface of an aliphatic polyester-based resin layer via an adhesive layer.

In recent years, as a solution to the problem that plastic waste has caused a great burden on the global environment, such as the impact on the ecosystem, the generation of toxic gases when burned, and global warming due to the large amount of combustion heat, Development of biodegradable plastics is becoming popular.

In particular, the carbon dioxide released when plant-derived biodegradable plastics are burned is originally in the air, so the carbon dioxide in the atmosphere does not increase. This is called carbon neutral, and under the Kyoto Protocol, which imposes carbon dioxide reduction targets, it is regarded as important and its active use is desired.

() From the viewpoint of biodegradability and carbon neutrality, aliphatic polyester resins have attracted attention as plant-derived plastics. In particular, polyhydroxyalkanoate (hereinafter sometimes referred to as PHA)-based resins, and among PHA-based resins, poly(3-hydroxybutyrate) homopolymer resins (hereinafter sometimes referred to as PHB), poly(3 -Hydroxybutyrate-co-3-hydroxyvalerate) copolymer resin (hereinafter sometimes referred to as PHBV), poly(3-hydroxybutyrate-co-3-hydroxyhexanoate) copolymer resin (hereinafter, PHBH), poly(3-hydroxybutyrate-co-4-hydroxybutyrate) copolymer resin, polylactic acid and the like are attracting attention.

Patent Document 1 discloses a molded article made of an aliphatic polyester resin composition containing a compound having an amide bond in a polyhydroxyalkanoate and pentaerythritol, and has improved moldability in injection molding, sheet processing, and the like. is stated.

Since polyhydroxyalkanoate has high biodegradability, it is rapidly decomposed after use and is being developed for various uses (for example, food packaging materials) as a resin that does not need to be recovered or incinerated.


In Patent Document 2, as a laminate that has heat resistance and biodegrades after use, polybutylene succinate is added to an adhesive layer between an aliphatic polyester resin layer made of polylactic acid and a polyvinyl alcohol resin layer. (hereinafter sometimes referred to as PBS) or polybutylene adipate terephthalate (hereinafter sometimes referred to as PBAT) using a modified polyester-based resin graft-modified with maleic anhydride is disclosed. .
Patent Document 3 discloses a laminated sheet in which a polylactic acid resin layer and a barrier layer made of an ethylene-vinyl alcohol copolymer are bonded using a modified polyolefin resin.

Due to the recent social trend toward stronger protection of the natural environment, there is a demand for biodegradable resins that are not partially biodegradable but completely biodegradable. In addition, as a biodegradation environment, not only biodegradability in an aerobic compost environment at a relatively high temperature (58 C or higher), but also biodegradability in an aerobic compost environment at room temperature (28 C) is required. If it exhibits biodegradability at room temperature, for example, sheets and containers made of biodegradable resin, specifically household packaging materials and tableware, can be treated as home compost after use.

Patent Documents 1 to 3 include examples of using biodegradable resins, but the molded bodies and laminates proposed here have a slow biodegradation rate at room temperature, and cannot satisfy recent demands. I didn't.

The laminates described in Patent Documents 2 and 3 have a high permeability to oxygen and water vapor, and could not be used for sheets or containers used as packaging materials for foods (such as coffee) that deteriorate in oxygen.

The present invention has been made in view of such a background. It is an object of the present invention to provide a biodegradable laminate having properties such as impact resistance and heat resistance, and having both water vapor barrier properties and oxygen barrier properties when used as a sheet or container.


The present inventors found that a biodegradable laminate in which a polyvinyl alcohol-based resin layer is laminated on at least one surface of an aliphatic polyester-based resin layer via an adhesive layer as a constituent material of an aliphatic polyester resin layer, Aliphatic polyester resin (A) containing repeating units derived from a group diol and repeating units derived from an aliphatic dicarboxylic acid as main structural units and polyhydroxyalkanoate containing 3-hydroxybutyrate units as main structural units By using an aliphatic polyester resin composition containing (B) and an inorganic filler (C), the biodegradation rate at room temperature is high, and mechanical properties such as impact resistance, heat resistance, and water vapor barrier properties The inventors have found that the oxygen barrier properties can be improved in a well-balanced manner, and have completed the present invention.

The adhesive resin composition composed of the modified polyester resin (D) obtained by the method has high biodegradability and can exhibit adhesiveness, and is optimal as a resin for the adhesive layer used in the biodegradable resin laminate. Since the inorganic filler (C) functions as a nucleating agent and effectively improves the moldability, the inclusion of the inorganic filler (C) makes it possible to produce a biodegradable laminate with excellent biodegradability. It becomes possible to provide it with moldability and productivity.

Aliphatic dicarboxylic acid refers to a compound in which two carboxyl groups are bonded to an aliphatic hydrocarbon group. As the aliphatic hydrocarbon group, a linear aliphatic hydrocarbon group is usually used, but it may have a branched structure, may have a cyclic structure, or may have a plurality of them. good.

High-molecular-weight polyester resins using these chain extenders (coupling agents) can also be produced using conventional techniques. Molecular weight polyester resins can be produced. Here, the weight-average molecular weight (Mw) of the polyester-based resin is obtained as a value converted to monodisperse polystyrene from a value measured by gel permeation chromatography (GPC) at a measurement temperature of 40 C. using chloroform as a solvent.

For example, when the above diisocyanate compound is used as a chain extender to further increase the molecular weight of the polyester resin, it is preferable to use a prepolymer having a weight average molecular weight of 20,000 or more, preferably 40,000 or more. When the weight-average molecular weight of the prepolymer is less than 20,000, the amount of diisocyanate compound used to increase the molecular weight increases, which may result in a decrease in heat resistance. Using such a prepolymer, a polyester resin having a urethane bond having a linear structure linked via a urethane bond derived from a diisocyanate compound is produced.

The pressure during chain extension is usually 0.01 MPa or more and 1 MPa or less, preferably 0.05 MPa or more and 0.5 MPa or less, more preferably 0.07 MPa or more and 0.3 MPa or less, but normal pressure is most preferable.

Regarding the reaction temperature during chain extension, the lower limit is usually 100C or higher, preferably 150C or higher, more preferably 190C or higher, most preferably 200C or higher, and the upper limit is usually 250C or lower, preferably 240C or lower, more preferably 240C or lower. is below 230C. If the reaction temperature is too low, the viscosity tends to be high, making uniform reaction difficult and requiring high stirring power. If the reaction temperature is too high, gelation and decomposition of the polyester resin tend to occur at the same time.

The chain extension time has a lower limit of usually 0.1 minute or more, preferably 1 minute or more, more preferably 5 minutes or more, and an upper limit of usually 5 hours or less, preferably 1 hour or less, more preferably 30 minutes or less. Most preferably it is 15 minutes or less. If the time for chain extension is too short, the effect of addition of the chain extender tends not to be exhibited. If the chain extension time is too long, gelation and decomposition of the polyester resin tend to occur at the same time.

The molecular weight of the aliphatic polyester-based resin (A) is usually 10,000 or more and 1,000, as a weight average molecular weight (Mw) obtained from the measurement value by gel permeation chromatography (GPC) using monodisperse polystyrene as a standard substance. 000 or less. Since the weight average molecular weight (Mw) of the aliphatic polyester resin (A) is advantageous in terms of moldability and mechanical strength, it is preferably 20,000 or more and 500,000 or less, more preferably 50,000 or more and 400,000 or less. is.

The melt flow rate (MFR) of the aliphatic polyester-based resin (A) is a value measured at 190 C. and a load of 2.16 kg based on JIS K7210 (1999), and is usually 0.1 g/10 min or more and 100 g/10 minutes or less. The MFR of the aliphatic polyester resin (A) is preferably 50 g/10 minutes or less, particularly preferably 30 g/10 minutes or less, from the viewpoint of moldability and mechanical strength. The MFR of the aliphatic polyester-based resin (A) can be adjusted by the molecular weight.



The melting point of the aliphatic polyester resin (A) is preferably 70C or higher, more preferably 75C or higher, and preferably 170C or lower, more preferably 150C or lower, and particularly preferably lower than 130C. . When there are multiple melting points, at least one melting point is preferably within the above range.
The elastic modulus of the aliphatic polyester resin (A) is preferably 180-1000 MPa.
If the melting point is outside the above range, moldability is poor, and if the elastic modulus is less than 180 MPa, problems with moldability and shape retention tend to occur. If the elastic modulus exceeds 1000 MPa, the impact resistance will deteriorate.

The method of adjusting the melting point and elastic modulus of the aliphatic polyester resin (A) is not particularly limited. It can be adjusted by adjusting the polymerization ratio or by combining them.

<Polyhydroxyalkanoate (B)>
Polyhydroxyalkanoate (hereinafter sometimes referred to as PHA) (B) has the general formula: [-CHR-CH 2 -CO-O-] (wherein R is an alkyl group having 1 to 15 carbon atoms ) and contains 3-hydroxybutyrate units as the main constituent.

Polyhydroxyalkanoate (B) preferably contains 80 mol % or more, preferably 85 mol % or more, of 3-hydroxybutyrate units as structural units from the viewpoint of moldability and heat resistance. Polyhydroxyalkanoate (B) is preferably produced by microorganisms.

Specific examples of polyhydroxyalkanoate (B) include poly(3-hydroxybutyrate) homopolymer resin, poly(3-hydroxybutyrate-co-3-hydroxypropionate) copolymer resin, poly(3- Hydroxybutyrate-co-3-hydroxyvalerate) copolymer resin, poly(3-hydroxybutyrate-co-3-hydroxyvalerate-co-3-hydroxyhexanoate) copolymer resin, poly(3-hydroxy butyrate-co-3-hydroxyhexanoate) copolymer resin, poly(3-hydroxybutyrate-co-3-hydroxyheptanoate) copolymer resin, poly(3-hydroxybutyrate-co-3-hydroxy octanoate) copolymer resin, poly(3-hydroxybutyrate-co-3-hydroxynonanoate) copolymer resin, poly(3-hydroxybutyrate-co-3-hydroxydecanoate) copolymer resin, poly (3-hydroxybutyrate-co-3-hydroxyundecanoate) copolymer resin, poly(3-hydroxybutyrate-co-4-hydroxybutyrate) copolymer resin, and the like.

Poly(3-hydroxybutyrate) homopolymer resin, poly(3-hydroxybutyrate-co-3-hydroxybutyrate), and poly(3-hydroxybutyrate)-co-3-hydroxyvale rate) copolymer resin, poly (3-hydroxybutyrate-co-3-hydroxyvalerate-co-3-hydroxyhexanoate) copolymer resin, poly (3-hydroxybutyrate-co-3-hydroxyhexanoate) poly(3-hydroxybutyrate-co-4-hydroxybutyrate) copolymer resin, particularly poly(3-hydroxybutyrate-co-3-hydroxyhexanoate) copolymer resin. preferable.

In the polyhydroxyalkanoate (B), 3-hydroxybutyrate (hereinafter sometimes referred to as 3HB) and comonomers such as 3-hydroxyhexanoate (hereinafter sometimes referred to as 3HH) copolymerized The composition ratio, that is, the monomer ratio in the copolymer resin, is 3-hydroxybutyrate / comonomer = 97/3 to 80/20 (mol% / mol%) from the viewpoint of molding processability and molded product quality. preferably 95/5 to 85/15 (mol%/mol%). If the comonomer ratio is less than 3 mol %, molding may be difficult because the molding temperature and the thermal decomposition temperature are close to each other. When the comonomer ratio exceeds 20 mol %, the crystallization of the polyhydroxyalkanoate (B) is slowed down, which may deteriorate the productivity.

Each monomer ratio in the polyhydroxyalkanoate (B) can be measured by gas chromatography as follows.

To about 20 mg of dry PHA, 2 ml of a mixture of sulfuric acid/methanol (15/85 (mass ratio)) and 2 ml of chloroform are added, and the mixture is sealed and heated at 100 C. for 140 minutes to obtain methyl ester of PHA decomposition product. After cooling, 1.5 g of sodium bicarbonate is added little by little to neutralize and allowed to stand until the evolution of carbon dioxide ceases. After adding 4 ml of diisopropyl ether and mixing well, the monomer unit composition of the PHA decomposition product in the supernatant is analyzed by capillary gas chromatography to determine the ratio of each monomer in the copolymer resin.

Average particle size (m) = 10000 x {6/(specific gravity of filler x specific surface area)}

<Method for producing aliphatic polyester resin composition>
The aliphatic polyester-based resin composition of the present invention includes an aliphatic polyester-based resin (A), a polyhydroxyalkanoate (B) and an inorganic filler (C), and other resins and other components used as necessary. Manufactured by

In this mixing step, the aliphatic polyester-based resin (A), the polyhydroxyalkanoate (B), the inorganic filler (C), and other resins and other components used as necessary are simultaneously mixed in a predetermined ratio, Alternatively, they are mixed in any order using a mixer such as a tumbler, a V-type blender, a Nauta mixer, a Banbury mixer, a kneading roll, and an extruder, and preferably melt-kneaded.

The kneader used in the mixing step may be a melt kneader. Although it does not limit the type of twin-screw extruder or single-screw extruder, melting according to the characteristics of the aliphatic polyester resin (A), polyhydroxyalkanoate (B) and inorganic filler (C) used A twin-screw extruder is more preferred for the purpose of achieving kneading.

The temperature during melt-kneading is preferably 120 to 220C. Within this temperature range, it is possible to shorten the time required for the melting reaction, prevent deterioration of color tone due to deterioration of the resin, prevent thermal decomposition, etc., and improve practical aspects such as impact resistance and moist heat resistance. physical properties can be further improved. From the same point of view, the melt-kneading temperature is more preferably 130 to 160C.

The melt-kneading time is not preferably lengthened unnecessarily from the viewpoint of more reliably avoiding deterioration of the resin, and is preferably 20 seconds or more and 20 minutes or less, more preferably 30 seconds or more and 15 minutes or less. It is preferable to set conditions such as melt-kneading temperature and time so as to satisfy this melt-kneading time.

Specific examples of aromatic diol components that provide aromatic diol units include xylylene glycol, 4,4-dihydroxybiphenyl, 2,2-bis(4-hydroxyphenyl)propane, 2,2-bis( 4'--hydroxyethoxyphenyl)propane, bis(4-hydroxyphenyl)sulfone, bis(4--hydroxyethoxyphenyl)sulfonic acid and the like. The aromatic diol component may be a derivative of an aromatic diol compound. A compound having a structure in which a plurality of aliphatic diol compounds and/or aromatic diol compounds are dehydrated and condensed with each other may also be used.

Specific examples of aromatic oxycarboxylic acid components that give aromatic oxycarboxylic acid units include p-hydroxybenzoic acid and p--hydroxyethoxybenzoic acid. The aromatic oxycarboxylic acid component may be a derivative of an aromatic oxycarboxylic acid compound. It may also be a compound (oligomer) having a structure in which a plurality of aliphatic oxycarboxylic acid compounds and/or aromatic oxycarboxylic acid compounds are dehydrated and condensed with each other. That is, an oligomer may be used as the raw material.

When optical isomers exist in the aromatic compound components that provide these aromatic compound units, any of the D-, L-, and racemic isomers may be used. Further, the aromatic compound component is not limited to the above examples as long as it can provide aromatic compound units. Furthermore, one aromatic compound component may be used alone, or two or more thereof may be used in any combination and ratio.

As the aliphatic-aromatic polyester resin, it is preferable to use an aromatic dicarboxylic acid component as a component that provides aromatic compound units. It is preferably 10 mol % or more and 80 mol % or less based on the total amount of group dicarboxylic acid units (100 mol %). Further, it is preferable to use terephthalic acid as the aromatic dicarboxylic acid component, and polybutylene terephthalate adipate and/or polybutylene terephthalate succinate resins are preferable as the aliphatic-aromatic polyester resin.

The aliphatic-aromatic polyester-based resin can be produced in the same manner as the aliphatic polyester-based resin (A) described above, using at least an aromatic compound component as a raw material.

The molecular weight of the aliphatic-aromatic polyester resin used in the present invention can be measured by gel permeation chromatography (GPC), and the weight average molecular weight (Mw) using monodisperse polystyrene as a standard is usually 10,000 or more and 1,000,000 or less. The weight average molecular weight (Mw) of the aliphatic-aromatic polyester resin is advantageous in terms of moldability and mechanical strength, so it is preferably 30,000 or more and 800,000 or less, more preferably 50,000 or more and 600,000. It is below.

The melt flow rate (MFR) of the aliphatic-aromatic polyester resin is a value measured at 190 C. and a load of 2.16 kg based on JIS K7210 (1999), and is usually 0.1 g / 10 minutes or more and 100 g / 10 minutes or less. From the viewpoint of moldability and mechanical strength, the MFR of the aliphatic-aromatic polyester resin is preferably 50 g/10 minutes or less, particularly preferably 30 g/10 minutes or less. The MFR of the aliphatic-aromatic polyester resin can be adjusted by the molecular weight.



The melting point of the aliphatic-aromatic polyester resin is usually 60 C. or higher, preferably 70 C. or higher, more preferably 80 C. or higher and 150 C. or lower, more preferably 140 C. or lower, particularly preferably 140 C. or lower. is below 120C. When there are multiple melting points, at least one melting point is preferably within the above range.
The elastic modulus of the aliphatic-aromatic polyester resin is preferably 180-1000 MPa.
If the melting point is outside the above range, moldability is poor, and if the elastic modulus is less than 180 MPa, problems with moldability tend to occur. On the other hand, if the elastic modulus exceeds 1000 MPa, the impact resistance tends to be poor.

The method of adjusting the melting point and elastic modulus of the aliphatic-aromatic polyester resin is not particularly limited. It can be adjusted by adjusting the copolymerization ratio of these or by combining them.

If the blending amount of the radical initiator is too small, sufficient graft polymerization may not occur and sufficient interlayer adhesion may not be obtained. If the blending amount of the radical initiator is too large, the cross-linking reaction of the polyester resin (d) proceeds and the extrusion rate during hot-melt molding is unstable, so that the appearance of the multilayer molded article tends to deteriorate.



The content of the unsaturated carboxylic acid and/or derivative thereof in the modified polyester resin (D) is not limited, but is usually 0.01% by mass or more, preferably 0.02% by mass or more, more preferably 0.03% by mass. [PVA-based resin layer]
The PVA-based resin layer in the biodegradable laminate of the present invention will be described.

Such a PVA-based resin layer is particularly responsible for the gas barrier properties of the laminate, and is laminated on at least one surface of the above-described aliphatic polyester-based resin layer via the above-described adhesive layer.

The PVA-based resin layer according to the present invention is a layer containing PVA-based resin as a main component, and usually contains 70% by mass or more, particularly 80% by mass or more, particularly 90% by mass or more of PVA-based resin. If the content of the PVA-based resin in the PVA-based resin layer is too low, gas barrier properties tend to be insufficient.

The PVA-based resin used in the PVA-based resin layer is a resin mainly composed of vinyl alcohol structural units, which is obtained by saponifying a polyvinyl ester-based resin obtained by copolymerizing a vinyl ester-based monomer. It is composed of a vinyl alcohol structural unit and a vinyl ester structural unit corresponding to the degree.

Vinyl ester monomers include vinyl formate, vinyl acetate, vinyl propionate, vinyl valerate, vinyl butyrate, vinyl isobutyrate, vinyl pivalate, vinyl caprate, vinyl laurate, vinyl stearate, vinyl benzoate, and versatic acid. Examples include vinyl and the like, but vinyl acetate is preferably used economically.


The PVA-based resin used in the present invention preferably has an average degree of polymerization (measured according to JIS K6726) of usually 200 to 1800, particularly 300 to 1500, especially 300 to 1000.
If the average degree of polymerization of the PVA-based resin is too small, the mechanical strength of the PVA-based resin layer tends to be insufficient. If the average degree of polymerization of the PVA-based resin is too large, the fluidity tends to be insufficient when the PVA-based resin layer is formed by hot-melt molding, and the moldability tends to decrease. may be subject to thermal decomposition.


The degree of saponification of the PVA resin used in the present invention (measured according to JIS K6726) is usually 80 to 100 mol%, particularly 90 to 99.9 mol%, especially 98 to 99.9 mol%. It is preferably used.
If the degree of saponification of the PVA-based resin is too low, gas barrier properties tend to deteriorate.

PVA-based resins include those obtained by copolymerizing various monomers during production of polyvinyl ester-based resins and saponifying them, and various modified PVA-based resins obtained by introducing various functional groups into unmodified PVA by post-modification. Resin can also be used.

Monomers used for copolymerization with vinyl ester monomers include olefins such as ethylene, propylene, isobutylene, -octene, -dodecene and -octadecene, 3-buten-1-ol and 4-pentene. -1-ol, 5-hexen-1-ol, 3,4-dihydroxy-1-butene and other hydroxy group-containing -olefins and their acylated derivatives, acrylic acid, methacrylic acid, crotonic acid, maleic acid , Maleic anhydride, unsaturated acids such as itaconic acid, salts thereof, monoesters or dialkyl esters, nitriles such as acrylonitrile and methacrylonitrile, amides such as diacetone acrylamide, acrylamide, methacrylamide, ethylene sulfonic acid, allyl Sulfonic acid, olefin sulfonic acids such as methallylsulfonic acid or salts thereof, alkyl vinyl ethers, dimethyl allyl vinyl ketone, N-vinyl pyrrolidone, vinyl chloride, vinyl ethylene carbonate, 2,2-dialkyl-4-vinyl-1,3 -Vinyl compounds such as dioxolane, glycerol monoallyl ether, 3,4-diacetoxy-1-butene, substituted vinyl acetates such as isopropenyl acetate and 1-methoxyvinyl acetate, vinylidene chloride, 1,4-diacetoxy-2- butene, vinylene carbonate, and the like.


Examples of PVA-based resins into which functional groups have been introduced by post-reaction include those having acetoacetyl groups by reaction with diketene, those having polyalkylene oxide groups by reaction with ethylene oxide, and hydroxyalkyl groups by reaction with epoxy compounds and the like. and those obtained by reacting aldehyde compounds having various functional groups with PVA.
The modified species in the modified PVA-based resin, that is, the content of structural units derived from various monomers in the copolymer, or the content of functional groups introduced by post-reaction, varies greatly depending on the modified species. However, the range of 1 to 20 mol %, especially 2 to 10 mol % is preferably used.

[Biodegradable laminate]
The biodegradable laminate of the present invention is formed by laminating a PVA-based resin layer on at least one surface of an aliphatic polyester-based resin layer via an adhesive layer, and usually 3 to 15 layers, preferably 3 It has a layer structure of to 7 layers, particularly preferably 5 to 7 layers. The configuration is not particularly limited, but when the aliphatic polyester resin layer is a, the PVA resin layer is b, and the adhesive layer is c, a/c/b, a/c/b/c/a, a/ Any combination is possible, such as b/c/b/c/b/a. The aliphatic polyester resin layer, PVA resin layer and adhesive layer may be the same or different.

Usually, in order to prevent deterioration of the gas barrier performance due to moisture absorption in the PVA-based resin layer, it is preferable to have a layer structure in which an aliphatic polyester-based resin layer is provided in the layer that contacts the outside air or contents containing moisture.

The thickness of the biodegradable laminate of the present invention is generally 1 to 30,000 m, particularly 3 to 13,000 m, particularly preferably 10 to 3,000 m.

The thickness of each layer constituting the biodegradable laminate is usually 0.4 to 14000 m, preferably 1 to 6000 m, particularly preferably 4 to 1400 m, for the aliphatic polyester resin layer. If the thickness of the aliphatic polyester-based resin layer is too thick, the biodegradable laminate tends to be too hard, and if it is too thin, the biodegradable laminate tends to be brittle.

The thickness of the PVA-based resin layer is generally 0.1-1000 m, preferably 0.3-500 m, particularly preferably 1-100 m. If the PVA-based resin layer is too thick, it tends to be hard and brittle.

The thickness of the adhesive layer is generally 0.1-500 m, preferably 0.15-250 m, particularly preferably 0.5-50 m. If the adhesive layer is too thick, the appearance may be poor, and if it is too thin, the adhesive strength tends to be weak.

The thickness ratio of the aliphatic polyester-based resin layer/PVA-based resin layer is usually 1 to 100, preferably 2.5 to 50, as the ratio of the total thicknesses when there are a plurality of layers. is. If the ratio is too large, the barrier properties tend to be low, and if it is too small, the biodegradable laminate tends to be hard and brittle.

When there are a plurality of adhesive layers, the ratio of the total thickness of the adhesive layer to the total thickness is usually 0.005 to 0.5, preferably 0.01 to 0.3. be. If the ratio is too large, the appearance tends to be poor, and if it is too small, the adhesion tends to be weak.

The biodegradable laminate of the present invention can be produced by a conventionally known molding method. Specifically, a melt molding method or a molding method from a solution state can be used. For example, as a melt molding method, an adhesive resin and a PVA-based resin are sequentially or simultaneously melt-extruded laminated onto an aliphatic polyester-based resin film or sheet. , a method of sequentially or simultaneously melt extrusion laminating aliphatic polyester resins, or a method of coextrusion of an aliphatic polyester resin, an adhesive resin and a PVA resin.

Examples of a method of molding from a solution state include a method of solution-coating a solution of an adhesive resin dissolved in a good solvent on an aliphatic polyester resin film, sheet, etc., followed by drying and then solution-coating an aqueous solution of a PVA-based resin. be done.

Among them, the melt molding method is preferable because it can be produced in one step and a biodegradable laminate having excellent interlayer adhesion can be obtained, and the coextrusion method is particularly preferably used. When the melt molding method is used, it is preferable to use a PVA-based resin having a 1,2-diol structure in the side chain.


The co-extrusion method includes, for example, an inflation method, a T-die method, a multi-manifold die method, a feed block method, and a multi-slot die method. A T-die, a round die, or the like can be used as the shape of the die for the out-of-die bonding method or the like.
The melt molding temperature during melt extrusion is usually in the range of 170 to 250C, preferably 180 to 230C.


The biodegradable laminate of the present invention may be further heat-stretched, and such stretching treatment is expected to improve strength and gas barrier properties.
In particular, in the biodegradable laminate of the present invention, when a PVA-based resin having a 1,2-diol structure in the side chain is used as the PVA-based resin, the stretchability is improved.


A known stretching method can be employed for the stretching treatment and the like.
For example, uniaxial stretching and biaxial stretching in which both edges of the multilayer structure sheet are gripped and widened; deep drawing method, vacuum forming method, pressure forming method, vacuum pressure forming method in which the multilayer structure sheet is stretched using a mold. a molding method using a mold such as a method; and a method of processing a preformed multilayer structure such as a parison by a tubular stretching method, a stretch blow method, or the like.

As such a stretching method, it is preferable to employ a uniaxial stretching method or a biaxial stretching method when a film or sheet-like molding is intended.

In the case of mold forming methods such as deep drawing, vacuum forming, air pressure forming, and vacuum pressure forming, the biodegradable laminate is uniformly heated in a hot air oven, a heater oven, or a combination of both. Then, it is preferably stretched by a chuck, plug, vacuum force, pneumatic force, or the like.

For cups, trays, etc., when the drawing ratio (molded product depth (mm) / maximum diameter (mm) of the molded product) is usually 0.1 to 3, deep drawing method, vacuum It is preferable to employ a mold molding method in which stretching is performed using a mold, such as a molding method, a pressure molding method, a vacuum pressure molding method, or the like.

The biodegradable laminate of the present invention thus obtained has strong adhesion between the aliphatic polyester resin layer and the adhesive layer and between the PVA resin layer and the adhesive layer.

When the above-mentioned modified polyester resin (D) is used as the adhesive resin of the adhesive layer, the basic skeleton thereof is the aliphatic polyester resin (d), so such a resin is also biodegradable. The biodegradable laminate of is also excellent in biodegradability.

The biodegradable laminate of the present invention has mechanical strength, flexibility, transparency, water resistance, moisture resistance, and biodegradability of the aliphatic polyester resin layer, mechanical strength, gas barrier properties, transparency, and It has biodegradability, the aliphatic polyester resin layer and the PVA resin layer are firmly adhered by the adhesive layer, and the adhesive layer can also be biodegradable, and is completely biodegradable and steam , which is excellent in oxygen barrier properties.

The biodegradable laminate of the present invention has chemical functions, electrical functions, magnetic functions, mechanical functions, friction/wear/lubricating functions, optical functions, thermal functions, surface functions such as biocompatibility, and the like. It is also possible to apply various secondary processing for the purpose of imparting. Examples of secondary processing include embossing, painting, adhesion, printing, metallizing (plating, etc.), machining, surface treatment (antistatic treatment, corona discharge treatment, plasma treatment, photochromism treatment, physical vapor deposition, chemical vapor deposition, coating, etc.).


[Use]
The biodegradable laminate of the present invention can be suitably used in a wide range of applications such as packaging materials for packaging liquids and powders such as various foods, medicines, miscellaneous goods, solids, agricultural materials, and construction materials. . Specific uses include injection molded products (e.g. fresh food trays, coffee capsules, fast food containers, outdoor leisure products, etc.), extrusion molded products (films, e.g. fishing lines, fishing nets, vegetation nets, water retention sheets, etc.). ), hollow molded articles (bottles, etc.), and the like.


In addition, other agricultural films, coating materials, fertilizer coating materials, laminated films, boards, stretched sheets, monofilaments, non-woven fabrics, flat yarns, staples, crimped fibers, creased tapes, split yarns, composite fibers, blow bottles, Shopping bags, garbage bags, compost bags, cosmetic containers, detergent containers, bleach containers, ropes, binding materials, sanitary coverstock materials, cooler boxes, cushioning films, multifilament, synthetic paper, surgical thread for medical use, sutures Threads, artificial bones, artificial skins, DDS such as microcapsules, wound dressings, and the like.
Among them, more preferably packaging materials such as packaging films, bags, trays, bottles, cushioning foams, fish boxes, etc., and agricultural materials such as mulching films, tunnel films, house films, sunshades , anti-grass sheets, ridge sheets, germination sheets, vegetation mats, nursery beds, flowerpots, and the like.

The molded article of the present invention is excellent in impact resistance, mechanical properties such as tear strength and tensile elongation at break, biodegradability, and the like, and is particularly preferably used for films and sheets.

<Biodegradability Test of Adhesive Resin Composition (Examples 1 to 10)>
Using the same resins as the modified polyester resins c-1 to c-10 used for the adhesive layers of Examples 1 to 10, single-layer sheets with a thickness of 100 m were obtained using a T-die molding machine. After the obtained monolayer sheet was stored in microbially active soil, the appearance was observed and the mass was measured, and the biodegradability was evaluated according to the following criteria. The biodegradability was measured after being stored in the soil for 10 weeks and taken out every two weeks (5 times in total). The maximum weight loss rate was defined as the weight loss rate for 2 weeks when the width of the weight loss was the largest among the measurements. Then, the 52nd week was calculated from the slope of the maximum weight loss rate. The evaluation temperature was 282C.
: 90% or more of the calculated value at the 52nd week is decomposed.
: Decomposes at 50% or more and less than 90% of the calculated value at the 52nd week.
: Decomposes at 15% or more and less than 50% as calculated at 52 weeks.
x: Degradation rate is 15% or less in the calculated value at 52 weeks.




<Biodegradability test of laminate (Examples 11 to 16, Comparative Examples 1 and 2)>
After storing the laminated sheet obtained by the above method in microbially activated soil for 12 months, the appearance was observed and the mass was measured, and the biodegradability was evaluated according to the following criteria. The evaluation temperature was 282C.
O: Completely biodegraded.
x: Almost no decomposition.
